segments.text: We'll sell them on the street, like street vendors, and just buy it for the size of it.
And then we'd all get together, and sometimes there would be an outfit function that would be going on.
And then you always had to, the upperclassmen always would have comments about your day.
And then everybody would get together and go to midnight y'all practice and would do that.
And then, at least in my case, there were always parents who would come in for the weekend.
And usually Saturday morning you'd get up and you'd be busy getting your uniform together and making sure everything was spotless.
And, of course, parents were allowed in the dorms, and so you want to make sure that your hole looked clean and neat and somewhat presentable.
And then typically, you know, you'd get together with your date and you'd fall out for the march into the games.
which is something every time I still go to a game, I still go to watch that portion of it.
And then after the game, there's usually, unfortunately when I was there, we didn't get to throw the year old leaders in the pond very often.
My fish year we did, because that was the year that Gene Stallings won the cotton ball.
But after that it got bad.
And then typically I have a big party
That's every night.
We're going to do stuff.
Seems like we usually want the hotels.
Usually your date would stay in a hotel.
But back then, no one had apartments.
You had to live on campus.
In fact, I can remember my senior year.
My two really close friends, we're twin brothers.
we all became data and got an apartment.

And I can remember having to get a doctor's from not permission, but a doctor saying because I had special dietary needs couldn't be fulfilled on campus that I need to live off campus, but you actually had to have something that will allow you to live off campus.
And so this would have been in the fall of 1970.
In that era, on that Saturday night football weekend, what time would you have gotten the young lady to her room?
How late did you all stay out?
Oh, back then, I'd say it was very proper.
It was like 12, 1 o'clock.
It wasn't like now.
How were the women treated?
Very respectful.
Very respectful.
I think that, well, mostly very respectful.

unfortunately can remember certain core trips when we would have let's say we're playing at Baylor and one of our buddies would have a girlfriend at Baylor and she would try to get everybody dates and sometimes if your date was not what you had hoped for Aggies could be pretty cool and there were certain things that would be done like pots taken to
See who had the worst date.
Yeah.
Let's see.
Was that a moose pot?
Something, yeah.
All right.
Are you aware that also the women used to sometimes from TWU have exactly the... Oh, I would think they would.
You know, I never went out with anybody from TWU.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
Now, in your era, were they still bringing down busloads, trainloads, upcassings?
No.
Okay.
A little bit after that, or a little bit before that.
As you look back on it,
How likely was it that something would happen involving a young man and a young woman on weekends at A&M then that was pretty extreme compared to today?
I would say it was very tame.
I truly don't even remember, like, guys trying to sneak girls into the room.
I mean, I don't just remember that.
It just didn't happen.
I mean, you may go to the hotel and stay with the girl overnight, but I don't recall ever...
I mean, people, it was still an era when there was, I think, a pretty high degree of propriety, particularly between males.
How often were you aware that somebody just got really drunk?
Oh, that happened quite frequently.
Is that right?
Not drunk to the extent of maybe having, you know, doing damage or anything physical.
But, you know, drink was a pretty,
Big part of going to school there.
And was there somebody then who literally was careful not to get drunk to be the driver?
No, there was no such thing as a designated driver, unfortunately.
And on some of the court trips, I can remember driving back to College Station when, in retrospect, there was probably none of us should have been driving.
And you talk about people who made a difference.
That brings up another thing.
I can remember at the end of my sophomore year,

um and it was right before christmas and my roommate and i had been out we had some drinks been having a good time and we're weaving back on the campus and getting ready to park and all of a sudden we see lights behind us like we're in deep trouble now and the campus cop guy gets out and of course we're underage we've been drinking and we've broken all these rules
And he took our names down, our driver's license down, and we're thinking, this is going to be horrible.
And he said, well, boys, he said, I'm going to think about this.
And he said, if you go home over the holidays, you may be getting something in the mail that says, here's a citation for underage drinking.
And he says, but if you don't get anything in the mail while you're at home over Christmas, how do you get home?
And so we sweat it.
I can remember going in the mailbox every day to check to see if it got anything.
And I think it was just his way of,
The what other evils did you all know about other than staying out late and drink?
Oh, and when you drank, what did people drink?
What were the beverages they were drinking?
Mostly just beer.
We weren't real sophisticated.
I can remember lots of kegs of beer.
A lot of times our outfit would go out and somebody would go out deer hunting and they'd get a deer and it would go, I can't remember where it was, but it was someplace off campus.
And we'd butcher the deer right there on the spot and barbecue it up and have kegs of beer.
I remember doing that quite a bit.
Did anybody ever butcher it in the dorm?
Not in the dorm, no.
Because I've heard two or three good stories about that.
You're talking about the evils, too.
I've been thinking about it in the late 60s, early 70s.
And I can say, I don't recall any drug use.
What drugs did you know existed?
I can say that my whole four years at A&M, I never went to a party, never smelled at the dorms, never...
Was there, did you know of any Aggie having marijuana in that year?
Probably back then, I wouldn't even know.
And were you aware of the words heroin or cocaine?
Probably.
And were you aware of any Aggies being the fathering children out of wedlock very much?
No, a couple of my Aggie buddies.
It was a very cold night, and as I recall, those windows at the end of the hallways

there were a group of people standing around, and it was a very, very cold night, and the glass was very cold, and one of the students in the dorm decided to move the people out there, and one of the warm, rearing, cold glass shattered.
And did he get any special treatment from any?
I think he had to go to the hospital to get it.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
Oh, oh, oh.
I was wondering if any upperclassmen made it.
No, no.
And I remember if it was one of our temporaries or if it was...
When I was there, I'm sure you see this picture all the time, Hector Gutierrez.
Hector and then Henry was two years ahead of me.
Hector was Corps Commander.
And I knew him well then and know him well now.
Great guy.
Did you ever have any personal interaction with Hector?
Well, because for a couple years we lived in the core dorm, or the core headquarters.
That's how we were seen.
Describe Hector.
He was what I would categorize as a true leader.
Examples of that leadership.
Henry Cisneros.
I think they both had very
They both had extraordinary leadership quality.
Did for either one of them, did you and your fellow Aggies think it meant anything plus or minus that they were Hispanic?
I don't think back then it didn't matter.
I certainly don't remember thinking that this is great that these Hispanics have got this great role.
But on the other hand, we didn't think why are these guys
You didn't think negatively.
You didn't think they... No, there's not a racial thing.
And for me, not growing up around any Hispanics, I certainly didn't have any prejudice from one way or the other.
But I remember them very differently.
And then we had a guy named Matt Carroll.
I think he was the Corps Commander my junior year.
And then Van Taylor was Corps Commander my senior year from my high school.
Oh, really?
Oh, see, I know Van then and now.
Oh, really?
I was on the Southwestern Bell Board for 17 years.
Describe undergraduate Van Taylor.
Serious all the time.
I mean, not to say that he was... Well, he wasn't fun, but he was a pretty serious guy.
And then another guy that he worked with was Commander...

did you and your fellow students think that the student leaders were selected truly on the basis of merit the corps commanders and people like that i didn't really get in the political aspects of it but i know my senior i thought that the band had um
been a good ROTC student, and I thought he deserved it.

Matt Carroll almost didn't get to be Corps Commander because we were, and I can't remember why, I can't remember if it was because where he grew up, but for some reason, the summer or the spring, as we were leaving for the summer, before the year that he was going to be Corps Commander, so this would have been the end of my sophomore year,
going into my junior year, and one in his senior year, for some reason, he was riding back down.
I don't know if he was, we dropped him off along the way or what the circumstances were, but we were going down Highway six.
And I decided I was going to pass somebody, of course, there was just a two lane road, and a car was coming the other direction.
And we managed to swerve off the road.
No.
Yeah.
And I think, as I recall, Matt's comments were something like, you know, and I'm not sure whatever happened.
He's done well.
I've forgotten what he's doing now, but he's done well.
Among you and your fellow students, which of the extracurricular student groups did you all respect most?
Which had the highest prestige?

rvs compared to the band and msc and all that which which single student office on the campus had the highest prestige well back when i was it's not an office but a core commander okay it's clearly the most important question and that was that was more than being student body president
I mean, like, I couldn't tell you who the student body president was each of the four years I was in school.
I can tell you who the corps commander was.
And MSC council president, you know, same thing.
But I remember that was important.
Yeah.
And Sconda was important, but, you know, back then, I don't know what the percentage was.
It was four versus Monterey, but it was still a big percentage.
What did you and your buddies think about the band?
There were BQs.
I think that, I mean, you love the band.
And again, to this day, every time I'm down for a football game, that's what I want to do is to go down and get that experience.
But I can say that I don't know that I ever was close to anybody that was in the band.
Physically, we were always up on that other, that north end of the quad, going two and four.
And so
for some reason just never had an opportunity to meet a lot of guys.
There were a lot of outfits that for one reason or another you were always close to.
For example, again, going back to my four friends that went there with the other two were in F2.
So I probably got to know or was close to the members of F2 as I was in my own company at one.
In fact, the two twins that

where my roommates my senior year were in f2 and then the room together and to this day are still extremely close in fact one of them just left to go back to houston yesterday because he spent the weekend with me oh good um let's see uh senior boots where'd you get them and how much they cost
Were they new?
Yeah, they were new.
It seems like they were about $400 or $500.
What did you do with them when you...
I still have them.
You still have them?
I still have them in my house.
My wife keeps saying, what are we ever going to do with these senior boots?
One day, about five years ago, I tried to try them on and couldn't get them on.
In fact, I need to get my Aggie ring resized because for some reason the last three or four months I can't get my senior ring resized.
Are those, what do those boots mean to you?
Why are they special?
I think it's probably just a sense of achievement.
I've gone through three years of, I was probably not a real military guy.
In fact, the summer for me, the summer between my sophomore and junior year when I had to sign a contract for ROTC,
I wasn't sure if the Army ROTC was what I wanted, so I talked to the Naval OCS guys about going to the Navy.
And that summer, so it would be the summer of 69, is when they had the first lottery.
And I can remember a bunch of our buddies getting together and watching the lottery.
Most of them had already planned on signing the contract.
And I decided that if I got a low number, that I was going to go ahead and go with the Naval OCS.
And if I got a high number,

then I was just going to go to DNC and I got a high number and that's what I did so I stayed in the court the last two years which was in a sense that was our fraternities back then were you aware that there were some secret fraternities no not when you were there apparently there were one or two but probably mostly on the
No, no, no.
In the Corps?
The TTs, the true Texans, and the swastikas go back to the 20s.
And almost nobody has been willing to say anything to me other than, yes, I heard there were some, but I don't know.
The swastikas use the swastika as their symbol, and it goes back at least to the 20s, maybe the teens.
So long before Adolf Hitler.
you about it.
And apparently their total purpose was to try to help members of their group become corps commander, RVs, senior class president and that sort of thing.
Let's see, what physical changes were there on the campus in your four years?
What was new?
What was, did it change much?
Do you remember?
12,000 students when we started and probably 16 or 17,000 when I graduated.
Make believe that I'd never heard of this man Earl Rutter.
Tell me about him as you students knew him.
I mean I can remember him as being larger than life.
Unplug up there.
Rutter's Rangers.
Remember all the stories of Rutter's Rangers and all of his heroic deeds?
We can remember, I can remember going by the house at Christmas time and serenading him with Christmas carols.
And just a truly remarkable, remarkable memory.
What word or words would you now describe the feeling which you and your colleagues had about him?
Admired him, respected him.
And now later in life, I know that he's been given a lot of credit for bucking the trend and allowing co-education and making the poor optional.
And so I think now we have to say forward thinking.
Probably, I can't think of too many people that I've ever come across in my lifetime that you would put into a hero status, but he would be one.
Let's see.
Did you ever hitchhike?
Oh, yeah.
Describe hit Aggie hitchhiking.
Put on the uniform and get out.
I mean, I hitchhiked, hitchhiked a lot from College Station orange.
And of course, again, this was back during the days of the Vietnam War.
And
Well, probably we've expected to have been heckled more than we were.
But I can recall very few incidents where, you know, people would yell stuff at you as you're out on the side of the road or whatever.
I'd say almost all positive experiences.
You caught the ride out at Eastgate.
Uh-huh.
And where in Houston was the ideal place to catch a ride, or was there a special?
There wasn't a special.
Usually you could get a ride with somebody leaving College Station and going to Houston.
I mean, most direct route, as you know, from College Station to Orange was not through Houston.
But if you were hitchhiking, you almost had to go that way.
You usually could hitch a ride with somebody to Houston and then get out and start thumbing it.
And usually right there on one of the major freeways close to Interstate 10.
I don't recall ever having any problems hitching a ride.
maybe one occasion once feeling a little bit uncomfortable, picked up a bunch of guys on Saturday night.
But really, I mean, that was an easy way to go back and forth.
In orange, where would you catch the ride?
Usually once I got to orange, it seems like I'd have a ride to come back to College Station.
Typically, it was if you got out of class earlier, you didn't have a ride down, but it seemed like I always had a ride back.
I don't
ever remember hitchhiking back from?
Do you have any hitchhike anecdote that would be appropriate share?
Actually, remember, it was really pretty, pretty simple.
Again, and probably by the time I was trying to catch like more of my, my freshman, sophomore years.
Never had any problem.
Let's see, we talked about getting dates.
Was Lupo around?
Did you have any relations with Little Army Lou?
No.
You didn't buy it?
I bought books and stuff.
But you never borrowed any money?
No, never.
Because I've heard of some good stories where he would stake them and so forth.
Do you remember any off-campus events
that kind of stunned you, either in the U.S. or worldwide?
This is the, you and I are chatting on the anniversary of the John Kennedy assassination.
So for me, that would be one of the, do you remember any when you were a student?
This would have been, I think it was actually the summer, probably between my sophomore and junior years, maybe my junior or senior year, when we landed on the moon for the first time.
I remember that.
Where were you, and what did you do?
I was at a Blood, Sweat, and Tears concert in Houston.
And I remember they interrupted the concert to say that we landed.
Any feelings?
I was pretty proud, yeah.
I mean, it was a pretty special time.
And, of course, you know, with us, so much of it was also things that were happening with the war.
What did you and your friends at A&M think about Vietnam?
I think there was probably not as gung-ho an attitude towards it as you would expect from a basic military college.
I don't recall that, again, there were a lot of demonstrations of

people necessarily radically against it, but I don't, at least in my outfit, I don't recall, you know, like everybody being gung-ho to say, let's hurry up and graduate so we can go fight the war in Vietnam.
So there wasn't the resistance to it, but there certainly wasn't anybody that was necessarily wanting to go over there.
Did some of your friends go to Vietnam and get killed?
Not close friends, but certainly no people did.

And I know people that, I had a friend that was able to avoid, he wasn't going to get drafted anyway, it didn't look like, but, I don't know exactly what, I remember he got braces put on his teeth, as a way to avoid getting drafted, because I guess they weren't orthodontists or something, but there was some reason that that was, I didn't know anybody that went to Canada, but, so I remember that.
Let's see, the campus, you mentioned Mr.
Rudder.
Were there any other famous campus dignitaries of your era?
Sports heroes?
Randy Mattson was still there.
He was still a pretty big figure because... What did you all think of Randy as a person?
I think everybody looked up to him.
He was a guy that had a world record, I guess.
And, no, he was always going to go out there.
remember Malin's nickname as attack officer the slink
and one of his buddies was the wage, the simplest tool known to man.
That was the Corps explanation.
And who was that?
No, I don't.
Who was the commandant of the Corps when you were there?
You see, I don't remember my secret.
Oh, the commandant, I don't know.
I don't even remember.
I don't remember who the band...
I'm a band director.
Colonel, was it...
Adam final review your junior and senior year describe feelings where did it happen and so forth you know I don't remember that's for some reason for me that wasn't a good living memory
Actually, I dropped out of the Corps finally the spring semester of my senior year.
So you didn't go through that.
So I didn't go in my senior year.
But I remember it was a big deal in my junior year, but I don't know why it wasn't a strong experience.
What did it feel like putting on those senior boots the first time?
That felt real special.
That was a pretty incredible experience.
That and my senior year.
Do you remember what the senior ring cost you?
It's now almost $500.
Well, I can remember because my first senior ring, I lost it to the Houston Lord football team, and my parents bought me another replacement ring.
I think back then it was like $350.
And that senior ring has been interesting because
for the 10 years you saw us in New York, I didn't wear it very frequently.
Because it's just kind of people back then.
That wasn't part of the jewelry.
And when we moved back out here, I started wearing it.
And it's just been amazing how my wife likes to get a lot of Aggies.
And how cross room.
Do you have any good Aggie ring story to offer?
Okay, good things happen.
I mean, I'm going to upgrade on airplanes.
Flight attendants in my first class.
But mostly it's just the camaraderie.
Things that happen as a result.
Do you remember silver taps first time or any of any time that was special?
Very

In fact, there's a letter in the court museum, and I don't remember, I'm sure I remember at the time, I don't remember too vividly right now, but it's a letter by a young man that wrote his parents about his first silver taps, and then the next week he was killed.
And the letter's in the court museum, and you can't...
you can't go by and read it.
To this day, I still read that letter and get chucked out.
And that occurred when I was in school.
Then I remember another thing that was kind of interesting.
I don't even remember what the final outcome was, but when I was there, there was a student that was killed in the process of committing the robbery at the Gibson store right there.
And I remember the big discussion of whether silver taps should be held for them.
And I don't remember if it actually was.
I think they did hold it.
Do you know that?
I was part of the process of where the paper flow went.
Probably in 1970.
I was among those who asked the question, was this person an Aggie or not?
If this person was an Aggie, isn't silver taps held for all Aggies?
If this person was not an Aggie, then there's no question.
And everybody agreed, yep, he was an Aggie, therefore we'll hold it.
Did all of you and all of your colleagues

respect the protocol of when to be silent when to keep the lights out and so forth i would say that was probably ahead of all the traditions right one certainly one that's made the most vivid memories all right these traditions uh list the traditions that are
